<abstract encodinganalog="5203_$a">Issei
		  businessman and civic leader who was removed from Seattle to the Minidoka
		  Relocation Center in Idaho during World War II</abstract>
<langmaterial>Collection materials are in 
										<language scriptcode="latn" langcode="eng" encodinganalog="546">English</language>.
									</langmaterial>
</did>
<bioghist encodinganalog="5450_" id="a2"><p>Yoshito Fujii was a Seattle Issei hotel owner and civic leader. During
		  the incarceration experience, he played an important role in the organization
		  of a viable community at the Minidoka Relocation Center in Hunt, Idaho. He
		  served as chairman of the first Board of Directors there and was later chairman
		  of the Community Council.</p></bioghist>
<odd encodinganalog="500" id="a5"><p audience="external"> The papers of Harry R. Hatate (folders 2  3)
		  also document the maintenance worker labor dispute at Minidoka (volume 3
		  below).</p></odd>
<acqinfo encodinganalog="541" id="a19"><p>The accession was donated to the Libraries by Yoshito Fujii on
		  December 26, 1979.</p></acqinfo>
